05326nam a22007095i 9781442697683DE-B159720210202111235.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210202t20212009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426976837 a10.3138/97814426976832doi  a(DE-B1597)575952  a(OCoLC)1233040854  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aB29 -- L59 1988 v. 11 7aPHI0220002bisacsh04a231/.0441 aLonergan, Bernard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Triune God :bDoctrines, Volume 11 /cBernard Lonergan; Robert Doran, S.J., H. Daniel Monsour. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2009  a1 online resource (880 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCollected Works of Bernard Lonergan ;v1100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tGeneral Editors' Preface -- tTranslator's Note -- tLATIN TEXT / ENGLISH TRANSLATION -- tPraefatio / Preface -- tIntroductio / Introduction -- tPARS PRIMA Praemittenda / PART 1 Prolegomena -- tPARS ALTERA Theses Quinque / PART 2 Five Theses -- tThesis 1: God the Father neither made his own and only Son out of preexisting matter nor created him out of nothing, but from eternity generates him out of his own substance as consubstantial with himself -- tThesis 2: The Holy Spirit, Lord and Life-giver, who proceeds from the Father and who spoke through the prophets, is to be adored and glorified together with the Father and the Son -- tThesis 3: Thus, the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit have one divinity, one power, one substance; they are, however, three hypostases or persons distinguished from one another by their proper attributes, which are relative; hence in God all things are one where there is no relational opposition -- tThesis 4: The Holy Spirit proceeds from the Father and the Son as from one principle and by a single spiration -- tThesis 5: The dogma of the Trinity, which is a mystery in the proper sense, cannot through natural human principles be either understood in itself or demonstrated from an effect. Even after revelation this remains true, although reason illumined by faith can, with God's help, progress towards some imperfect analogical understanding of this mystery -- tAppendices -- tAbbreviations -- tBibliography of Modern Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWritten in Latin for students at the Gregorian University in Rome, Bernard Lonergan's De Deo Trino (The Triune God) is a monumental two-part examination of trinitarian theology published initially in 1961 and again, in revised form, in 1964. The first part, the pars dogmatica, is here translated into English in an edition that includes the original Latin on facing pages. The work begins with the Prolegomena, which traces the dialectical development of trinitarian doctrine by Christian thinkers from the time of the New Testament to the Council of Nicea (AD 325). Following is a discussion of five theses outlining the evolution of the principal features of trinitarian doctrine from the New Testament through the patristic era. Along with its companion volume on systematics, The Triune God: Doctrines represents the most comprehensive treatment of trinitarian theology in recent centuries. This English translation ensures that Lonergan's masterpiece will at last be available in its entirety to contemporary readers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Feb 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh1 aDoran, S.J., Robert, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aShields, Michael G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMonsour, H. Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDoran, Robert M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relator